e two peoples into contact, most prominently with the Viking invasion of Ireland. In the famous Second Battle of Moytura, gods such as Lug, Balor, and the Dagda participated in the conflict that distinguished this invasion. Pseudohistory, which consists of both secular and ecclesiastical fictions, arose in this nexus of peoples and myth and spilled over into other contexts such as chronological annals. Scandinavian gods such as Odin, Balder, Thor, and Loki feature in the Edda of Snorri Sturluson and the history of the Danes by Saxo Grammaticus. This volume explores such written works alongside archaeological evidence from earlier periods through fresh approaches that challenge entrenched views.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aCeltsxHistory. 0aMythology, Celtic. 0aMythology, Norse. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 4aMedieval Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aMythology, Vikings, Irish Pagan Gods, Saxo Grammaticus, Snorri Sturluson.1 aBek-Pedersen, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergholm, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarey, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalaky Nagy, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Elizabeth A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKudenko, Ksenia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyle, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyle, Emily, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMurray, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a